class Solution {
    public long maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values) {
        List<Integer>[] g = new ArrayList[values.length];
        Arrays.setAll(g, e -> new ArrayList<>());
        g[0].add(-1);
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            int x = e[0], y = e[1];
            g[x].add(y);
            g[y].add(x);
        }
        long ans = 0;
        for (int v : values) {
            ans += v;
        }
        return dfs(0, -1, g, values) / 2;
    }

    private long dfs(int x, int fa, List<Integer>[] g, int[] values) {
        long loss = 0;
        for (int y : g[x]) {
            if (y != fa) {
                loss += dfs(y, x, g, values);
            }
        }
        return Math.max(values[x], loss);
    }
}
```
The code first constructs the tree from the given edges. Then, it computes the maximum score that can be obtained by adding the values of nodes along the paths from the root to any leaf node. It uses depth-first search (DFS) to explore the tree, and for each node, it chooses the maximum value between the current node's value and the sum of the values on the paths from its children to leaves. Finally, it returns the maximum score that can be obtained by adding the values of nodes along the paths from the root to any leaf node.

