class Solution {
    public long maximumSubarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {
        long ans = Long.MIN_VALUE;
        long sum = 0;
        Map<Integer, Long> minS = new HashMap<>();
        for (int x : nums) {
            long s1 = minS.getOrDefault(x - k, Long.MAX_VALUE / 2);
            long s2 = minS.getOrDefault(x + k, Long.MAX_VALUE / 2);
            ans = Math.max(ans, sum + x - Math.min(s1, s2));
            minS.merge(x, sum, Math::min);
            sum += x;
        }
        return ans > Long.MIN_VALUE / 4 ? ans : 0;
    }
}
```
The given code is a solution to the problem using dynamic programming and a hash map to keep track of the minimum sum up to each element. It iterates over the array and for each element, it calculates the maximum sum of a good subarray ending at the current element. This is done by subtracting the minimum sum up to the current element that is at most k away from the current element, either in the positive or negative direction. The maximum sum is then updated if necessary.

