class Solution {
    public int minimumArrayLength(int[] nums) {
        int m = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int x : nums) {
            m = Math.min(m, x);
        }

        for (int x : nums) {
            if (x % m > 0) {
                return 1;
            }
        }

        int cnt = 0;
        for (int x : nums) {
            if (x == m) {
                cnt++;
            }
        }
        return cnt;
    }
}

Explanation:

The method `minimumArrayLength(int[] nums)` first finds the smallest number in the array `nums` and stores it in the variable `m`. Then it checks if all elements in the array `nums` are divisible by `m`. If they are not, it returns 1 as only one element will be left in the array after performing the operation. If all elements are divisible by `m`, it counts the number of elements equal to `m` in the array `nums` and returns this count as the length of the minimum array that can be obtained after performing the operations.

